  "prompt": "Is money laundering a crime?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense in most jurisdictions around the world. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal (or \"clean\"). This typically involves three stages:\n\n1. **Placement**: Introducing the illicit funds into the financial system.\n2. **Layering**: Concealing the source of the funds through a series of complex transactions and bookkeeping tricks.\n3. **Integration**: Making the funds available to the criminal as apparently legitimate wealth.\n\nMoney laundering is a serious crime because it enables criminals to profit from illegal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, and terrorism, while undermining the integrity of financial systems and institutions.\n\nLaws against money laundering are enforced by various national and international bodies, such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), which sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Penalties for money laundering can include substantial fines, imprisonment, and seizure of assets.\n\nIf you suspect or are involved in money laundering activities, it is crucial to seek legal advice immediately to understand your rights and obligations.",
